defs.docs: Composable primitives for asynchronous computations

attributes.value: must_use = "futures are lazy and do nothing unless consumed"

defs.name: of
defs.docs: Returns a future that will immediately succeed with the supplied value.

defs.name: error
defs.docs: Returns a future that will immediately fail with the supplied error.

defs.name: lazy
defs.docs:
Returns a future that won't kick off its async action until
 a consumer registers interest.

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Future<U, E>

defs.name: map_err
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Future<T, U>
defs.docs:
Returns a new future with an identical value as the original. If the
 original future fails, apply the given function on the error and use
 the result as the error of the new future.

defs.name: spawn
defs.docs:
Returns a `Future` representing the completion of the given closure.
 The closure will be executed on a newly spawned thread.

defs.name: to_stream
defs.docs: An adapter that converts any future into a one-value stream

defs.name: Complete
defs.docs: An object that is used to fulfill or reject an associated Future.

attributes.value: must_use = "Futures must be completed or they will panic on access"

defs.name: complete
defs.docs: Fulfill the associated promise with a value

defs.name: fail
defs.docs:
Reject the associated promise with an error. The error
 will be wrapped in `Async::Error::Failed`.

defs.name: join
defs.value: fn <J, T, E> (asyncs: J) -> Future<T, E>

defs.name: Join
defs.value: Join<T: Send + 'static, E: Send + 'static>: Sized + Send + 'static

defs.name: defer
defs.value: fn <R, A> (task_runner: R, future_in: A) -> Future<A::Value, A::Error>
defs.docs:
This method defers a task onto a task runner until we can complete that call.
 Currently we only support using a ThreadPool as the task runner itself.

defs.name: background
defs.value: fn <R, F, T> (task_runner: R, closure: Box<F>) -> Future<T, ()>
defs.docs:
This method backgrounds a task onto a task runner waiting for complete to be called.
 Currently we only support using a ThreadPool as the task runner itself.

defs.name: select
defs.value: fn <S, E> (asyncs: S) -> Future<(u32, S), E>

defs.name: sequence
defs.docs:
Returns a `Stream` consisting of the completion of the supplied async
 values in the order that they are completed.

attributes.value: must_use = "streams are lazy and do nothing unless consumed"

defs.name: pair
defs.docs: Creates a new `Stream`, returning it with the associated `Sender`.

defs.name: empty
defs.docs: Returns a Stream that will immediately succeed with the supplied value.

defs.name: collect
defs.docs:
Asyncronously collects the items from the `Stream`, returning them sorted by order of
 arrival.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: Synchronously iterate over the `Stream`

defs.name: each
defs.docs:
Sequentially yields each value to the supplied function. Returns a
 future representing the completion of the final yield.

defs.name: filter
defs.docs:
Returns a new stream containing the values of the original stream that
 match the given predicate.

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, mut f: F) -> Stream<U, E>
defs.docs:
Returns a new stream representing the application of the specified
 function to each value of the original stream.

defs.name: map_async
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, action: F) -> Stream<U::Value, E>
defs.docs:
Returns a new stream representing the application of the specified
 function to each value of the original stream. Each iteration waits for
 the async result of the mapping to realize before continuing on to the
 next value.

defs.name: map_err
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Stream<T, U>
defs.docs:
Returns a new stream with an identical sequence of values as the
 original. If the original stream errors, apply the given function on
 the error and use the result as the error of the new stream.

defs.name: process
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, in_flight: usize, f: F) -> Stream<U::Value, E>

defs.name: reduce
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, init: U, f: F) -> Future<U, E>
defs.docs:
Aggregate all the values of the stream by applying the given function
 to each value and the result of the previous application. The first
 iteration is seeded with the given initial value.

defs.name: reduce_async
defs.value: fn <F, U, X> (self, init: X, action: F) -> Future<X, E>
defs.docs:
Aggregate all the values of the stream by applying the given function
 to each value and the realized result of the previous application. The
 first iteration is seeded with the given initial value.

defs.name: take
defs.docs:
Returns a stream representing the `n` first values of the original
 stream.

defs.name: Sender
defs.docs:
The sending half of `Stream::pair()`. Can only be owned by a single task at
 a time.

defs.name: send
defs.value: fn (mut self, val: T) -> BusySender<T, E>
defs.docs:
Attempts to send a value to its `Stream`. Consumes self and returns a
 future representing the operation completing successfully and interest
 in the next value being expressed.

defs.name: fail
defs.docs: Terminated the stream with the given error.

defs.name: abort
defs.docs:
Fails the paired `Stream` with a cancellation error. This will
 eventually go away when carllerche/syncbox#10 lands. It is currently
 needed to keep the state correct (see async::sequence)

defs.name: send_all
defs.docs: Send + 'static all the values in the given source

defs.name: send_all
defs.value: fn <E2> (self, sender: Sender<Self::Value, E2>) -> Future<Sender<Self::Value, E2>, (Self::Error, Sender<Self::Value, E2>)>

defs.name: Timer
defs.docs: Provides timeouts as a `Future` and periodic ticks as a `Stream`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new timer backed by a thread pool with 5 threads.

defs.name: with_capacity
defs.docs: Creates a new timer backed by a thread pool with `capacity` threads.

defs.name: timeout_ms
defs.docs: Returns a `Future` that will be completed in `ms` milliseconds

defs.name: interval_ms
defs.docs: Return a `Stream` with values realized every `ms` milliseconds.

defs.name: Async
defs.docs: A value representing an asynchronous computation

defs.name: is_ready
defs.docs: Returns true if `expect` will succeed.

defs.name: is_err
defs.docs: Returns true if the async value is ready and has failed

defs.name: poll
defs.docs: Get the underlying value if present

defs.name: expect
defs.docs: Get the underlying value if present, panic otherwise

defs.name: ready
defs.docs:
Invokes the given function when the Async instance is ready to be
 consumed.

defs.name: receive
defs.docs: Invoke the callback with the resolved `Async` result.

defs.name: await
defs.docs:
Blocks the thread until the async value is complete and returns the
 result.

defs.name: fire
defs.docs: Trigger the computation without waiting for the result

defs.name: and
defs.docs:
This method returns a future whose completion value depends on the
 completion value of the original future.

defs.name: and_then
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Future<U::Value, Self::Error>
defs.docs:
This method returns a future whose completion value depends on the
 completion value of the original future.

defs.name: or
defs.docs:
This method returns a future whose completion value depends on the
 completion value of the original future.

defs.name: or_else
defs.value: fn <F, A> (self, f: F) -> Future<Self::Value, A::Error>
defs.docs:
This method returns a future whose completion value depends on the
 completion value of the original future.
